the American legal system with respect to questions of law. As Gary Lawson shows, legal claims are inherently objects of proof, and whether or not the law acknowledges the point openly, proof of legal claims is just a special case of the more general norms governing proof of any claim. As a result, similar principles of evidentiary admissibility, standards of proof, and burdens of proof operate, and must operate, in the background of claims about the law. This book brings these evidentiary principles for proving law out of the shadows so that they can be analyzed, clarified, and discussed. Viewing legal problems through this lens of proof illuminates debates about everything from constitutional interpretation to the role of stipulations in litigation. Rather than prescribe resolutions to any of those debates, Evidence of the Law instead provides a set of tools that can be used to make those debates more fruitful, whatever one’s substantive views may be. As lawyers, judges, and legal subjects confront uncertainty about what the law is, they can, should, and must, Lawson argues, be guided by the same kinds of abstract considerations, structures, and doctrines long used to make determinations about questions of fact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEvidence (Law) - Philosophy. 0aEvidence (Law)xPhilosophy. 0aEvidence (Law)zUnited States. 0aEvidence. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aevidence sets.  aevidence.  alegal claims.  alegal epistemology.  aproof of law.  aproof.  astandards of proof.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643205240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226432199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226432199/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago 